==Etymology==
*The name {{W|Pius}} is derived from the Latin word ''pius'', which despite being similar to the English word 'pious', has a different shade of meaning: ''that is, it refers to one who has reverence for law, government, as well as order.'' Thus it is particularly appropriate for a head of the [[Department of Magical Law Enforcement]] and [[Minister for Magic]].
**This name may also be based on the word 'pious', though -- 'pious' means ''devoutly religious'', or ''having or expressing reverence for a God''; a fitting name for (though [[Imperius Curse|Imperiused]]) the puppet Minister for [[Tom Riddle|Lord Voldemort]], for whom reverence, loyalty, and a strong outward image was crucial to his power.
*Thicknesse, meanwhile, is a likely allusion to the word 'thick,' a British-origin slang word. Someone who is 'thick' is considered stupid, dumb, or otherwise obedient or non-thinking. In this sense, Thicknesse may refer to Thicknesse's being under the Imperius Curse, being a mere puppet, not thinking for himself, and obeying Voldemort's every command.
**This is noticeably reflected in foreign language translations of Thicknesse's name; in Serbian translations, Thicknesse was renamed 'Pije Glupsije', the word "glupsije" being derived from the word "glup" which means "dumb". In Italian, Thicknesse was renamed 'Pius O'tusoe', which sounds like the word "ottuso", an Italian word for "dumb".
**The Swedish translation, on the other hand, names him "Pius Korpulens", with "korpulens" being a play on the more common meaning of "thickness", as it's an archaic word (also existing in English, as "corpulence") roughly meaning "the state of being plump, stout, fat, overweight, or obese, usually due to overeating".

